  <para style="h">1 Timothy</para>
  <para style="toc1">The Epistle of 1 Timothy</para>
  <para style="toc2">1 Timothy</para>
  <para style="toc3">1 Tim.</para>
  <para style="mt2">THE EPISTLE OF</para>
  <para style="mt1">1 TIMOTHY</para>
  <!--   ************   -->
  <!--   Introduction   -->
  <!--   ************   -->
  <para style="imt">Introduction</para>
  <para style="ipi">Paul’s instructions to one of his closest assistants, his “dear son” Timothy, has been broadened into
    guidelines which all Christian churches should follow. Paul doesn’t just give sterile rules to do this,
    that, and the other, but gets into the details of what’s going on inside the hearts and minds of various
    people—especially the nefarious ones, adding a lot of color to the epistles he sent to Timothy.</para>
  <para style="ipi">The text is typical of Paul: mastery of Greek, an extensive vocabulary, Western thought, ambiguous in
    parts due to its brevity or to knowledge privy to the writer and the reader.</para>
  <para style="ib"></para>
  <!--   **********   -->
  <!--   Chapter  1   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="1" style="c" sid="1TI 1" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1TI 1:1" />Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus according to the command of God our savior and Christ Jesus our hope:<verse eid="1TI 1:1" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1TI 1:2" />To Timothy, a genuine son<char style="sup">[a]</char> in <char style="it">the </char>Faith:
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="1TI 1:2">Grace, mercy, peace—from God <char style="it">the </char>Father and from Christ Jesus our Lord.<verse eid="1TI 1:2"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1TI 1:3" />Just as I advised you to remain in Ephesus while on <char style="it">my</char> way to Macedonia so that
        you would impress upon certain individuals not to go about teaching things which are…shall we say…different<char
        style="sup">[b]</char> <verse eid="1TI 1:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1TI 1:4" />or to take myths or endless genealogies seriously (the very things which generate a lot of <char style="it">stupid
        </char>questions), more <char style="it">seriously</char> than <char style="it">one takes </char>godly
        stewardship, a stewardship which is by means of<char style="it"> </char>faith<char style="sup">[c]</char>.<verse eid="1TI 1:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1TI 1:5" />But the bottom line of the command <char style="it">that they’re charged with</char> is love from a clean
        heart and a good conscience, <verse eid="1TI 1:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1TI 1:6" />of which a few people in particular have veered off into a ditch of senseless discussion, <verse eid="1TI 1:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1TI 1:7" />wanting to be instructors in the Law <char style="it">of Moses</char>, not understanding what they’re
        saying or the implications of what they insist is true.<verse eid="1TI 1:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1TI 1:8" />Now we know that the Law is just fine if someone were to use it legitimately, <verse eid="1TI 1:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1TI 1:9" />knowing this for certain: law (i.e., the Law of Moses in particular or any code of right and wrong for
        that matter) was put in place for a reason, not for someone who lives right but for the lawless, for
        those who refuse to submit to authority, for those who aren’t pious, for those who murder their fathers,
        their mothers, their brothers, <verse eid="1TI 1:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1TI 1:10" />for fornicators (i.e., those who indulge in gross sexual immorality), for homosexuals, kidnappers, liars,
        perjurers, and <char style="it">for </char>anyone who supplants what’s been put into place with something
        different than healthy doctrine, <verse eid="1TI 1:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1TI 1:11" /><char style="it">doctrine </char>which is in line with the glorious Gospel of the God Who is blessed,
        <char style="it">doctrine </char>that I’ve been entrusted with.<verse eid="1TI 1:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1TI 1:12" />I have grace for my empowerment in Christ Jesus our Lord, since he trusted me enough to make me a minister<char
        style="sup">[d]</char>, <verse eid="1TI 1:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1TI 1:13" /><char style="it">me</char> who used to be a blasphemer, a persecutor, and one who was insolent and violent—but
        no—He showed mercy since I did these things when I didn’t know better <char style="it">while I was </char>in
        unbelief, <verse eid="1TI 1:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="1TI 1:14" />and the grace of our Lord proliferated out of bounds with faith and love which is in Christ Jesus.<verse eid="1TI 1:14" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="1TI 1:15" />This statement is trustworthy and from any point of view is worth being accepted: Christ Jesus came into
        the world to save sinners, I myself being the foremost. <verse eid="1TI 1:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="1TI 1:16" />In spite of this I was shown mercy, so that in me foremost Christ Jesus would demonstrate every kind
        of patience imaginable, with a view towards those in the future who will be believing in<char style="sup">[e]</char>
        him resulting in eternal life.<verse eid="1TI 1:16" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="1TI 1:17" />Now to the King of the eternities—to the Incorruptible, Invisible, Singular God—<char style="it">be </char>honor
        and glory forever and ever. Amen (i.e., let us pause a moment for that remark to sink in).<verse eid="1TI 1:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="1TI 1:18" />These things I’m charging you with, I entrust to you, Timothy <char style="it">my dear </char>son, according
        to the prophesies over you which were given beforehand to lead you on your way, so that you would “serve
        in the army” <char style="it">so to speak</char> among them and be a fine soldier, <verse eid="1TI 1:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="1TI 1:19" />having faith and a good conscience, which some, having shoved aside things pertaining to the Faith, are
        shipwrecked (i.e., their lives have been devastated), <verse eid="1TI 1:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="1TI 1:20" />among whom are Hymenaeus and Alexander, whom I’ve handed over to Satan so that he would train them (train
        them like one trains a child) not to talk trash or blaspheme.<verse eid="1TI 1:20" />
    </para>
