  <!--   Chapter  3   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="3" style="c" sid="1TI 3" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1TI 3:1" />You can count on this statement being true: if someone aspires to be a bishop<char style="sup">[a]</char>
        (i.e., a head pastor), he desires to do something excellent<char style="sup">[b]</char>. <verse eid="1TI 3:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1TI 3:2" />So a bishop candidate must have no moral character flaws<char style="sup">[c]</char>; must be the husband
        of one woman<char style="sup">[A]</char> (i.e., not divorced and remarried); self-controlled and exercise
        moderation in vices such as drinking; be sensible, serious, and level-headed; be respected, held in high
        esteem, and honorable; be hospitable, able to reach out to others, and likes and can work with people
        who are different than himself; be capable of giving instructions to others or teaching them; <verse eid="1TI 3:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1TI 3:3" />not be a heavy drinker or have a drinking problem; not a bully, a brawler, or someone who gets into fights,
        but yielding, gentle, courteous, and tolerant instead, and avoids fights; not fondly attached to money;<verse eid="1TI 3:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1TI 3:4" /><verse eid="1TI 3:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1TI 3:5" />but if someone can’t preside over his own household, how will he look after God’s household?); <verse eid="1TI 3:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1TI 3:6" />not a newbie, so that he won’t become full of himself or conceited and fall to <char style="it">the </char>Accuser’s
        (the Devil’s) true accusations of guilt. <verse eid="1TI 3:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1TI 3:7" />Outsiders must have a good report to give about him, so that he won’t fall into disgrace: the Accuser’s
        trap<char style="sup">[d]</char>.<verse eid="1TI 3:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1TI 3:8" />Likewise, deacons<char style="sup">[a]</char> (i.e., associate pastors and ministry directors) <char
        style="it">must be</char> honorable and respectable; not insincere or say one thing one moment and contradict
        it another; not consumed with drinking<char style="sup">[e]</char>; not always trying to make a fast
        buck through shady business practices; <verse eid="1TI 3:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1TI 3:9" />possessing the mystery of the Faith in a clean conscience. <verse eid="1TI 3:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1TI 3:10" />Let these <char style="it">candidates </char>first be examined and approved, then let them serve as deacons
        <char style="it">after </char>being <char style="it">found </char>to have no moral character flaws.<verse eid="1TI 3:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1TI 3:11" /><char style="it">The ministers’</char> wives must be honorable and respectable as well; not slanderers;
        self-controlled and exercising moderation in vices such as drinking; faithful in all respects. <verse eid="1TI 3:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1TI 3:12" />Make sure<char style="sup">[f]</char> deacons are the husbands of one wife (i.e., have not been divorced
        and remarried); do a good job of presiding over their children and over their household. <verse eid="1TI 3:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1TI 3:13" />In fact, those who have done a good job serving as a deacon take a big step forward in their own lives<char
        style="sup">[g]</char> and acquire much boldness and confidence in <char style="it">the </char>Faith
        which is in Christ Jesus.<verse eid="1TI 3:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="1TI 3:14" />I’m writing these things to you and hoping to visit you post-haste. <verse eid="1TI 3:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="1TI 3:15" />But in case I’m delayed, <char style="it">I’m writing these things to you now </char>so that you would
        know for a fact how <char style="it">the </char>house of God, which very thing is the church of the Living
        God, a pillar and a chief supporting base of the truth, must be run<char style="sup">[h]</char>. <verse eid="1TI 3:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="1TI 3:16" />And great, admittedly, is the mystery<char style="sup">[B]</char> of piety:
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16"><char style="it">He</char> who appeared in <char style="it">the </char>flesh</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16">Was declared righteous in spirit<char style="sup">[i]</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16">Was seen by angels</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16">Was preached to the Gentiles</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16">Was believed by the world</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1TI 3:16">Was taken up in glory<verse eid="1TI 3:16"/>
    </para>
